    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="TolE0438">
<l>mutalī reṇṇiṉoṟṟu rakara māku</l>
<l>mukaram varuta lāvayi ṉāṉa</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>It is said that, if [the words denoting] <foreign xml:lang="ta">oṉṟu</foreign> ' one ' to <foreign xml:lang="ta">oṉpatu</foreign> ' nine '</l>
<l>[are followed by <foreign xml:lang="ta">pattu</foreign> ' ten '], the consonant of the ' standing '</l>
<l><foreign xml:lang="ta">pattu</foreign> following the <foreign xml:lang="ta">a</foreign> is replaced by <foreign xml:lang="ta">āytam,</foreign> and the final overshort</l>
<l><foreign xml:lang="ta">u</foreign> with its preceding consonants is dropped, except with the ending</l>
<l>of <foreign xml:lang="ta">āṛu</foreign> ' six '.<note place="foot">I.e., if the preceding word is any of the numerals from one to nine (with
          the exception of six), and the succeeding word is <foreign xml:lang="ta">pattu, pattu &gt;
          pahtu</foreign> by replacing the <foreign xml:lang="ta">t</foreign> with the <foreign xml:lang="ta">āytam,</foreign> and in the preceding word, the final <foreign xml:lang="ta">u</foreign> and the preceding plosive disappear : eg. <foreign xml:lang="ta">aintu + pattu &gt; aimpahtu.</foreign> Aphorisms 439-445 explain the
          individual cases.</note></l>
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
